  <Section eyebrow="By deployment" title="The guarantee differs, and stating that plainly is part of the design." tone="tinted">
    <table class="w-full text-sm">
      <thead>
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-200 text-left">
          <th class="pb-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-neutral-900">Property</th>
          <th class="pb-2 pr-4 font-semibold text-neutral-900">Self-hosted</th>
          <th class="pb-2 font-semibold text-neutral-900">Managed</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="text-neutral-600">
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-100">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">Node discards raw inputs; stores only the signed proof</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">Yes — architectural invariant</td>
          <td class="py-3">Yes — architectural invariant</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-neutral-100">
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">Odal can access stored data</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">No — not present in the deployment</td>
          <td class="py-3">Constrained by access controls, audit logging, and contract</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">Odal can sign on the operator's behalf</td>
          <td class="py-3 pr-4">No</td>
          <td class="py-3">No — the operator holds the signing keys</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </Section>

  <Section eyebrow="How it works" title="The mechanism, not the promise.">
    <ol>
      <li>
        <strong>Import.</strong> Product data arrives at your node — CSV, Excel,
        or an ERP export. This happens on infrastructure you control.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Validate.</strong> The node validates locally against versioned
        sector schemas. Validation is a pure function — no network calls, no
        third-party API.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Sign.</strong> Your private signing key — generated and held
        in-process on your infrastructure — signs the validated passport.
        The result is a signature cryptographically bound to your published
        <code>did:web</code> identity.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Publish.</strong> Only the signed passport becomes publicly
        resolvable via QR and GS1 Digital Link. The raw input is discarded.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Verify.</strong> Any consumer, authority, or recycler verifies
        the signature against your public DID Document. Verification does not
        require Odal to be online or to exist.
      </li>
    </ol>
  </Section>

</Base>
